instruction:
Java runs on over 3 billion devices. Android phones, ATMs, airline booking systems — Java is everywhere.

Every Java program has the same skeleton:
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // your code here
    }
}
```

`System.out.println()` prints a line. Hit **Run** and see your first Java program execute.

starter:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, Java!");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Java is powerful.");
        // TODO: add two more println calls
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // This is a single-line comment
        System.out.println("Comments are invisible to Java.");

        /*
         * This is a multi-line comment.
         * Very useful for longer explanations.
         */
        System.out.println("But your code runs fine.");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // TODO: print your name and age using + concatenation
        System.out.println("Name: " + "Alex");
        System.out.println("Age: " + 25);
        System.out.println("Combined: " + "Alex" + " is " + 25);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(10 + 3);
        System.out.println(10 - 3);
        System.out.println(10 * 3);
        System.out.println(10 / 3);   // integer division!
        System.out.println(10.0 / 3); // decimal division
        System.out.println(10 % 3);   // remainder
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("First line")
        System.out.PrintLn("Second line");
    }
}

public class Main {
    /*
     * Every Java program starts here.
     * Java looks for a class named Main with this exact method signature.
     */
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Class: " + Main.class.getSimpleName());
        System.out.println("Method: main");
        System.out.println("Ready to learn Java!");
    }
}
